  <!-- Fun Facts -->
  <div class="facts-card">
    <h3>Capsaicin Science Fun Facts &#x1F52C;</h3>
    <div class="facts-grid">
      <div class="fact-item">
        <div class="fact-icon">&#x1F9EC;</div>
        <h4>Capsaicin Tricks Your Brain</h4>
        <p>Capsaicin binds to TRPV1 receptors — the same receptors that detect actual heat above 109°F. Your brain literally thinks your mouth is on fire, even though no tissue damage occurs.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-item">
        <div class="fact-icon">&#x1F426;</div>
        <h4>Birds Can't Feel the Burn</h4>
        <p>Birds lack the TRPV1 receptor variant that responds to capsaicin. Peppers evolved spiciness specifically to deter mammals while letting birds (who spread seeds better) eat freely.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-item">
        <div class="fact-icon">&#x1F3C3;</div>
        <h4>The Endorphin Rush</h4>
        <p>Eating hot peppers triggers endorphin and dopamine release — the same "runner's high" chemicals. This is why spice lovers describe a euphoric rush after eating extreme peppers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-item">
        <div class="fact-icon">&#x1F9C8;</div>
        <h4>Milk Beats Water Every Time</h4>
        <p>Casein protein in dairy binds to capsaicin and washes it away. Water is useless because capsaicin is oil-soluble — water just spreads the burn to more of your mouth.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-item">
        <div class="fact-icon">&#x2699;&#xFE0F;</div>
        <h4>Pure Capsaicin = 16 Million SHU</h4>
        <p>Pure crystalline capsaicin scores 16,000,000 SHU. It's used in medical research for pain management, pepper spray (2-5.3M SHU), and even cancer research.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-item">
        <div class="fact-icon">&#x1F4AA;</div>
        <h4>You Can Build Tolerance</h4>
        <p>Regular capsaicin exposure desensitizes TRPV1 receptors over time. A chili-head eating daily can tolerate 10x what a spice newbie can — but tolerance fades if you stop.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-item">
        <div class="fact-icon">&#x1F48A;</div>
        <h4>Health Benefits Are Real</h4>
        <p>Studies link regular spicy food consumption to 14% lower mortality risk, boosted metabolism (up to 8%), reduced inflammation, and improved cardiovascular health.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-item">
        <div class="fact-icon">&#x1F321;&#xFE0F;</div>
        <h4>Hottest Is Getting Hotter</h4>
        <p>In 1994, the Red Savina (577K SHU) was world's hottest. By 2023, Pepper X hit 2.69M SHU — a 4.7x increase in under 30 years of selective breeding.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>

<div class="content">
  <h2>Understanding the Scoville Heat Scale</h2>
  <p>The <strong>Scoville scale</strong> measures the pungency (spicy heat) of chili peppers and other spicy foods in <strong>Scoville Heat Units (SHU)</strong>. Created by American pharmacist Wilbur Scoville in 1912, the original test involved diluting pepper extract with sugar water until a panel of tasters could no longer detect heat. Today, <strong>High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC)</strong> provides precise, objective measurements of capsaicinoid concentration.</p>
  <p>The scale ranges from 0 SHU (bell peppers) to over 16 million SHU (pure capsaicin). Most everyday peppers and hot sauces fall between 500 and 350,000 SHU — the range where flavor and heat intersect most enjoyably.</p>

  <h2>Heat Level Categories Explained</h2>
  <h3>Mild (0 - 2,500 SHU)</h3>
  <p>Perfect for spice beginners and family cooking. <strong>Bell peppers</strong>, <strong>banana peppers</strong>, <strong>pepperoncini</strong>, and <strong>poblanos</strong> offer great flavor with minimal heat. These peppers are all about taste — sweet, earthy, and tangy notes that enhance dishes without overpowering.</p>

  <h3>Medium (2,500 - 30,000 SHU)</h3>
  <p>The sweet spot for most home cooks. <strong>Jalape&ntilde;os</strong>, <strong>serranos</strong>, <strong>chipotles</strong>, and sauces like <strong>Sriracha</strong> and <strong>Tabasco</strong> live here. Noticeable heat that adds excitement without requiring a glass of milk. Most restaurant "spicy" dishes fall in this range.</p>

  <h3>Hot (30,000 - 100,000 SHU)</h3>
  <p>Where things get serious. <strong>Cayenne</strong>, <strong>chile de arbol</strong>, and <strong>piri piri</strong> peppers deliver significant heat that demands respect. Great for spice enthusiasts who want a real kick in their cooking.</p>

  <h3>Very Hot (100,000 - 350,000 SHU)</h3>
  <p><strong>Habaneros</strong>, <strong>Scotch bonnets</strong>, and <strong>bird's eye chilis</strong> dominate this range. A little goes a long way — a single habanero can heat an entire pot of chili. These peppers also bring incredible tropical and fruity flavors.</p>

  <h3>Extreme (350,000 - 1,000,000 SHU)</h3>
  <p>The <strong>ghost pepper</strong> (bhut jolokia) territory. These peppers are not for casual eating — they're used sparingly in cooking and more commonly found in extreme hot sauces. Handle with gloves, avoid touching your face, and use tiny amounts.</p>

  <h3>Nuclear (1,000,000+ SHU)</h3>
  <p><strong>Carolina Reapers</strong>, <strong>Trinidad Scorpions</strong>, and <strong>Pepper X</strong> are bred specifically for maximum heat. Eating these raw is an extreme sport that can cause intense pain, nausea, and capsaicin cramps. They're most commonly used in extract hot sauces and eating challenges.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the Scoville scale and how is it measured?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">The Scoville scale measures the pungency (spiciness) of chili peppers and spicy foods in Scoville Heat Units (SHU). Originally created by pharmacist Wilbur Scoville in 1912 using a taste test panel, modern measurements use High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC) to precisely quantify capsaicinoid concentration. A bell pepper scores 0 SHU while pure capsaicin reaches 16,000,000 SHU.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the hottest pepper in the world?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Pepper X currently holds the Guinness World Record at 2,693,000 SHU, surpassing the Carolina Reaper (2,200,000 SHU). Both were created by Ed Currie of PuckerButt Pepper Company. The Dragon's Breath and Apollo peppers have claimed higher unofficial measurements but lack verified Guinness records.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Why do some people enjoy eating extremely spicy food?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Capsaicin triggers pain receptors (TRPV1) which causes the brain to release endorphins and dopamine, creating a natural "high" similar to a runner's high. Over time, repeated exposure desensitizes these receptors, allowing spice lovers to tolerate and enjoy increasingly hotter foods. This is sometimes called "benign masochism" — the thrill of pain in a safe context.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What helps cool your mouth after eating something too spicy?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Dairy products like milk, yogurt, and ice cream are most effective because casein protein binds to capsaicin and washes it away. Sugar and starchy foods like bread or rice also help absorb capsaicin. Avoid water — capsaicin is oil-soluble, not water-soluble, so water just spreads the heat around your mouth.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Is eating very spicy food dangerous or harmful?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">For most healthy adults, eating spicy food is safe and may even have health benefits including boosted metabolism, anti-inflammatory effects, and improved cardiovascular health. However, extremely hot peppers (1M+ SHU) can cause intense pain, nausea, vomiting, and in rare cases, capsaicin cramps. People with GERD, IBS, or stomach ulcers should be cautious with very spicy foods.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

